      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Conclusion: An outlier can distort correlation estimates: (1) if the outlier is a measurement or data entry error, it should be removed, (2) if there is no legitimate reason to remove it, it should be checked to see if it violates the assumptions before performing the correlation estimate, (3) if there is no legitimate reason to remove it and the assumptions are violated, non-parametric tests or bootstrapping techniques should be used."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "TQMKHNk6VPLJ"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "##1.5. Small Sample Size"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "y_FahS9suTtu"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Imagine you are testing whether two groups differ on some outcome. If the sample size is small, the results of the statistical test may vary widely simply due to random sampling variation. In this exercise, we will simulate 2 studies to see how small sample sizes can lead to unstable results, making it easier to miss real effects and sometimes giving misleadingly large significant findings."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "XuZuBETJBgwH"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Step 1: testing for a real difference (real effect)**\n",
        "\n",
        "The true difference between the groups is 2: Therefore an effect exists\n",
        "\n",
        "So:\n",
        "\n",
        "If the test detects a significant difference (p < 0.05) → correct result\n",
        "\n",
        "If the test fails to detect it (p ≥ 0.05) → Type II error (false negative)\n",
        "\n",
        "Note that sample size controls how well we can detect real effects !"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9dpDNjuRoQXI"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# Set values:\n",
        "n <- 10; meandiff <- 2;\n",
        "my_sd <- 2\n",
        "# Perform t-test:\n",
        "t.test( rnorm(n, sd = my_sd), rnorm(n, sd = my_sd) + meandiff)\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 208
        },
        "id": "YKUXEYz4m54a",
        "outputId": "820556ca-067e-4bfc-cce9-1cdaaee5a7fd"
      },
      "execution_count": 95,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "\n",
              "\tWelch Two Sample t-test\n",
              "\n",
              "data:  rnorm(n, sd = my_sd) and rnorm(n, sd = my_sd) + meandiff\n",
              "t = -3.5753, df = 15.651, p-value = 0.002605\n",
              "alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0\n",
              "95 percent confidence interval:\n",
              " -5.689649 -1.449155\n",
              "sample estimates:\n",
              "mean of x mean of y \n",
              "-1.096956  2.472446 \n"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "print(\"Proportion of false negatives in 10000 simulations when sample size=10\")\n",
        "mean(replicate(10000, t.test(rnorm(10,2), rnorm(10,2) + meandiff)$p.value > 0.05))\n",
        "print(\"Proportion of false negatives in 10000 simulations when sample size=1000\")\n",
        "mean(replicate(10000, t.test(rnorm(1000,2), rnorm(1000,2) + meandiff)$p.value > 0.05))"
      ],
