    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Conclusion: Small sample sizes produce unstable estimates and low statistical power, making it more likely to miss real effects and to overestimate the size of significant findings. Researchers should aim to use sufficiently large samples to ensure adequate statistical power."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "V5EB-PDaufv3"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "##1.6. Significant but Meaningles"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2AR_8GbYH491"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "Imagine you collect a very large dataset and run a regression to study whether a variable x influences an outcome y. After estimating the model, you find that the coefficient of x is highly statistically significant, with a very small p-value.\n",
        "\n",
        "At first sight, this might suggest that the model captures an important relationship. However, when you look at the goodness of fit, you discover that the model explains almost none of the variation in the data. In this exercise, we illustrate how statistically significant results can arise even when the model has very little explanatory power."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VN7fuBUIIcrs"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Step 1: data and analysis**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Ko7OIGK5Ixeq"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "set.seed(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Large sample\n",
        "n <- 10000\n",
        "\n",
        "# Predictor\n",
        "x <- rnorm(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Outcome with almost no relationship to x\n",
        "y <- 0.02*x + rnorm(n)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Linear regression\n",
        "model <- lm(y ~ x)\n",
        "\n",
        "summary(model)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
          "height": 329
        },
        "id": "oicY9DhlmqPt",
        "outputId": "70a6fb7d-77ff-451d-9722-d3a6a7b689b3"
      },
      "execution_count": 5,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "display_data",
          "data": {
            "text/plain": [
              "\n",
              "Call:\n",
              "lm(formula = y ~ x)\n",
              "\n",
              "Residuals:\n",
              "    Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max \n",
              "-4.2940 -0.6793 -0.0144  0.6648  3.7265 \n",
              "\n",
              "Coefficients:\n",
              "             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)  \n",
              "(Intercept) -0.004159   0.009908  -0.420   0.6747  \n",
              "x            0.024742   0.009788   2.528   0.0115 *\n",
              "---\n",
              "Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1\n",
              "\n",
              "Residual standard error: 0.9908 on 9998 degrees of freedom\n",
              "Multiple R-squared:  0.0006387,\tAdjusted R-squared:  0.0005388 \n",
              "F-statistic:  6.39 on 1 and 9998 DF,  p-value: 0.01149\n"
            ]
          },
          "metadata": {}
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "**Step 2: plotting**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5XhypAlWI2un"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "plot(x, y,\n",
        "     pch=16,\n",
        "     col=rgb(0,0,0,0.2),\n",
        "     main=\"Significant relationship but very low R²\")\n",
        "\n",
        "abline(model, col=\"red\", lwd=2)"
      ],
